# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: a
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:a/7-letter] Where ⟨ʔ⟩ is not available, not being in the basic Latin alphabet, it is sometimes replaced by a question mark ⟨?⟩, which is its official representation in the SAMPA transcription scheme.
[src:a/7-letter] In Skwomesh or Squamish, ⟨ʔ⟩ may be replaced by the digit ⟨7⟩ (see image above).
[src:a/7-letter] In Unicode, four graphic variants of the glottal stop letter are available.
[src:a/7-letter] Additionally, there are two graphic variants with a stroke, both used in phonetic transcriptions.
[src:a/7-letter] Other common symbols for the glottal stop sound are variants of the punctuation mark apostrophe that was the historical basis of the glottal stop letters.
[src:a/7-letter] These include the 9-shaped modifier letter apostrophe, ⟨ʼ⟩, which is probably the most common (and the direct ancestor of ⟨ʔ⟩), the 6-shaped ʻokina of Hawaiian, ⟨ʻ⟩, and the straight-apostrophe shaped saltillo of many languages of Mexico, which has the case forms ⟨Ꞌ ꞌ⟩.
[src:a/7-letter] In Unicode 1.0, only the unicase and superscript variants were included.
[src:a/7-letter] In version 4.1 (2005), an uppercase character was added, and the existing unicase character was redefined as its lowercase.
[src:a/7-letter] Then, in version 5.0 (2006), it was decided to separate the cased and caseless usages by adding a dedicated lowercase letter.
[src:a/7-letter] The IPA character is first from left, while the extended Latin alphabet characters are third and fourth from left.
[src:a/8th-century] The **8th century** is the period from 701 (represented by the Roman numerals DCCI) through 800 (DCCC) in accordance with the Julian Calendar.
[src:a/8th-century] In the historiography of Europe the phrase **the long 8th century** is sometimes used to refer to the period of circa AD 660–820.
[src:a/8th-century] The coast of North Africa and the Iberian Peninsula quickly came under Islamic Arab domination.
[src:a/8th-century] The westward expansion of the Umayyad Empire was famously stopped at the siege of Constantinople by the Byzantine Empire and the Battle of Tours by the Franks.
[src:a/8th-century] The tide of Arab conquest came to an end in the middle of the 8th century.
[src:a/8th-century] In Europe, late in the century, the Vikings, seafaring peoples from Scandinavia, begin raiding the coasts of Europe and the Mediterranean, and go on to found several important kingdoms.
[src:a/8th-century] In Asia, the Pala Empire is founded in Bengal.
[src:a/8th-century] The Tang dynasty reaches its pinnacle under Chinese Emperor Xuanzong.
[src:a/a-list] An **A-list** actor is a major movie star, or one of the most bankable actors in a film industry.
[src:a/a-list] The A-list is part of a larger guide called *The Hot List*, which ranks the bankability of 1,400 movie actors worldwide, and has become an industry-standard guide in Hollywood.
[src:a/a-list] American entertainment journalist James Ulmer, the guide's creator, has also developed a version including directors, the *Hot List of Directors*.
[src:a/a-list] The **Ulmer scale** categorizes the lists into A+, A, B+, B, C, and D listings.
[src:a/a-list] Similarly, in India, there is three-tier strategy, tier-1, tier-2 and tier-3, which are based on the saleability and box office collection capability of a star.
[src:a/a-list] In popular usage outside the film industry, an A-list celebrity is any person with an admired or desirable social status.
[src:a/a-list] Even socialites with popular press coverage and elite associations have been termed as A-list celebrities.
[src:a/a-list] Similarly, less popular persons and current teen idols are referred to as B-list celebrities – and the ones with lesser fame as C-list ones.
[src:a/a-list] In 2000, *Entertainment Weekly* interpreted a C-list celebrity as "that guy (or sometimes that girl), the easy-to-remember but hard-to-name character actor".
[src:a/a-list] The *D-list* is for someone whose celebrity is so obscure that they are generally only known for appearances as celebrities on panel game shows and reality television.
[src:a/a-list] Kathy Griffin, an American comedian who became widely known for her frequent appearances on such programs, used the term in a tongue-in-cheek manner for her 2005 TV special *The D-List* and her 2005 TV series *Kathy Griffin: My Life on the D-List*.
[src:a/a-list] The term "D-list" is derived from the lowest rating used for the Ulmer scale.
[src:a/a-list] Other successive letters of the alphabet beyond D, as in the terms *E-list* and *Z-list*, are sometimes used for exaggeration or comic effect but effectively have the same meaning as *D-list*.
[src:a/a] It is similar in shape to the Ancient Greek letter alpha, from which it derives.
[src:a/a] The uppercase version consists of the two slanting sides of a triangle, crossed in the middle by a horizontal bar.
[src:a/a] The lowercase version is often written in one of two forms: the double-storey |a| and single-storey |ɑ|.
[src:a/a] The latter form is commonly used in handwriting and fonts based on it, especially fonts intended to be read by children, and is also found in italic type.
[src:a/a] In English, the name of the letter is the *long A* sound, pronounced /ˈeɪ/.
[src:a/a] Its name in most other languages matches the letter's pronunciation in open syllables.
[src:a/a] The earliest known ancestor of A is *aleph*—the first letter of the Phoenician alphabet—where it represented a glottal stop [ʔ], as Phoenician only used consonantal letters.
[src:a/a] In turn, the ancestor of aleph may have been a pictogram of an ox head in proto-Sinaitic script influenced by Egyptian hieroglyphs, styled as a triangular head with two horns extended.
[src:a/a] When the ancient Greeks adopted the alphabet, they had no use for a letter representing a glottal stop—so they adapted the sign to represent the vowel /a/, calling the letter by the similar name *alpha*.
[src:a/a] In the earliest Greek inscriptions dating to the 8th century BC following the Greek Dark Ages, the letter rests upon its side.
[src:a/a] However, in the later Greek alphabet it generally resembles the modern capital form—though many local varieties can be distinguished by the shortening of one leg, or by the angle at which the cross line is set.
[src:a/a] The Etruscans brought the Greek alphabet to the Italian Peninsula, and they left the form of alpha unchanged.
[src:a/a] When the Romans adopted the Etruscan alphabet to write Latin, the resulting form used in the Latin script would come to be used to write many other languages, including English.
[src:a/a] During Roman times, there were many variant forms of the letter A.
[src:a/a] First was the monumental or lapidary style, which was used when inscribing on stone or other more permanent media.
[src:a/a] There was also a cursive style used for everyday or utilitarian writing, which was done on more perishable surfaces.
[src:a/a] Due to the perishable nature of these surfaces, there are not as many examples of this style as there are of the monumental, but there are still many surviving examples of different types of cursive, such as majuscule cursive, minuscule cursive, and semi-cursive minuscule.
[src:a/a] Variants also existed that were intermediate between the monumental and cursive styles.
[src:a/a] The known variants include the early semi-uncial (c.
[src:a/a] 4th–8th centuries), and the late semi-uncial (c.
[src:a/a] At the end of the Roman Empire (5th century CE), several variants of the cursive minuscule developed through Western Europe.
[src:a/a] Among these were the semi-cursive minuscule of Italy, the Merovingian script in France, the Visigothic script in Spain, and the Insular or Anglo-Irish semi-uncial or Anglo-Saxon majuscule of Great Britain.
[src:a/a] By the ninth century, the Caroline script, which was very similar to the present-day form, was the principal form used in book-making, before the advent of the printing press.
[src:a/a] This form was derived through a combining of prior forms.
[src:a/a] 15th-century Italy saw the formation of the two main variants that are known today.
[src:a/a] These variants, the *Italic* and *Roman* forms, were derived from the Caroline Script version.
[src:a/a] The Italic form ⟨ɑ⟩, also called *script a*, is often used in handwriting; it consists of a circle with a vertical stroke on its right.
[src:a/a] In the hands of medieval Irish and English writers, this form gradually developed from a 5th-century form resembling the Greek letter tau ⟨τ⟩.
[src:a/a] The Roman form ⟨a⟩ is found in most printed material, and consists of a small loop with an arc over it.
[src:a/a] Both derive from the majuscule form ⟨A⟩.
[src:a/a] In Greek handwriting, it was common to join the left leg and horizontal stroke into a single loop, as demonstrated by the uncial version shown.
[src:a/a] Many fonts then made the right leg vertical.
[src:a/a] In some of these, the serif that began the right leg stroke developed into an arc, resulting in the printed form, while in others it was dropped, resulting in the modern handwritten form.
[src:a/a] Graphic designers refer to the *Italic* and *Roman* forms as *single-decker a* and *double decker a* respectively.
[src:a/a] Italic type is commonly used to mark emphasis or more generally to distinguish one part of a text from the rest set in Roman type.
[src:a/a] There are some other cases aside from italic type where *script a* ⟨ɑ⟩, also called *Latin alpha*, is used in contrast with Latin ⟨a⟩, such as in the International Phonetic Alphabet.
[src:a/a] In English, ⟨a⟩ is the indefinite article (with the alternative form *an* when followed by a vowel).
[src:a/a] The double ⟨aa⟩ sequence does not occur in native English words, but is found in some words derived from foreign languages such as *Aaron* and *aardvark*.
[src:a/a] However, ⟨a⟩ occurs in many common digraphs, all with their own sound or sounds, particularly ⟨ai⟩, ⟨au⟩, ⟨aw⟩, ⟨ay⟩, ⟨ea⟩ and ⟨oa⟩.
[src:a/a] In most languages that use the Latin alphabet, ⟨a⟩ denotes an open unrounded vowel, such as /a/, /ä/, or /ɑ/.
[src:a/a] An exception is Saanich, in which ⟨a⟩—and the glyph ⟨Á⟩—stands for a close-mid front unrounded vowel /e/.
[src:a/a] The Latin letters ⟨A⟩ and ⟨a⟩ have Unicode encodings U+0041 A LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A and U+0061 a LATIN SMALL LETTER A.
[src:a/a] These are the same code points as those used in ASCII and ISO 8859.
[src:a/a] There are also precomposed character encodings for ⟨A⟩ and ⟨a⟩ with diacritics, for most of those listed above; the remainder are produced using combining diacritics.
[src:a/a] Variant forms of the letter have unique code points for specialist use: the alphanumeric symbols set in mathematics and science, Latin alpha in linguistics, and halfwidth and fullwidth forms for legacy CJK font compatibility.
[src:a/a] The Cyrillic and Greek homoglyphs of the Latin ⟨A⟩ have separate encodings U+0410 А CYRILLIC CAPITAL LETTER A and U+0391 Α GREEK CAPITAL LETTER ALPHA.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Lloyd's Register is not affiliated with Lloyd's of London, but emerged from the same professional and social circles that historically met at Lloyd's Coffee House, from which both organisations took their name.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] In popular discourse the two organisations are often confused.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] The organisation was named after a seventeenth-century coffee house in London that was frequented by merchants, marine underwriters, and others associated with shipping.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] The coffee house owner, Edward Lloyd, helped them to exchange information by circulating a printed sheet of all the news he heard.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] In 1760, the Register Society was formed by the customers of the coffee house who assembled the *Register of Shipping*, the first known register of its type.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Between 1800 and 1833, a dispute between shipowners and underwriters resulted in each group publishing a list—the *"Red Book"* and the *"Green Book"*.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Both parties came to the verge of bankruptcy.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] They reached agreement in 1834 to unite and form Lloyd's Register of British and Foreign Shipping, establishing a General Committee and charitable values.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] In 1914, with an increasingly international outlook, the organisation changed its name to Lloyd's Register of Shipping.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Thus the best classification "A1", from which the expression *A1* or *A1 at Lloyd's* is derived, first appeared in the 1775–76 edition of the Register.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] The Register, with information on all seagoing, self-propelled merchant ships of 100 gross tons or greater, is published annually.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] A vessel remains registered with Lloyd's Register until it is sunk, wrecked, hulked, scrapped or withdrawn from the Register by the vessel's owner.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] The Register was published formerly by the joint venture company of Lloyd's Register-Fairplay, which was formed in July 2001 by the merger of Lloyd's Register's Maritime Information Publishing Group and Prime Publications Limited.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Lloyd's Register sold its share of the venture to IHS Markit in 2009.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] The American Lloyd's Registry of American and Foreign Shipping was established in 1857, and the *American Lloyd's Register of American and Foreign Shipping* issued from at least 1859 until at least 1883 by the "Board of American Lloyd's".
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] In 2020, Lloyd's Register sold its energy business, which was rebranded Vysus Group and in 2021 sold its Business Assurance & Inspection Services division.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] In 2022, LR acquired OneOcean Group, a marine software and digital services company, to head up a new digital services division.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] In July 2012, the organisation converted from an Industrial and Provident Society to a Company Limited by Shares, named Lloyd's Register Group Limited, with the new Lloyd's Register Foundation as the sole shareholder.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] At the same time the organisation gave to the Foundation a substantial bond and equity portfolio to assist it with its charitable purposes.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] It benefits from continued funding from the group's operating arm.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Lloyd's Register has changed and expanded over the last 250 years with the industrial revolutions - from a time when steam engines were developed for mechanical production to the digital and cyber technology of today.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] The latter developments are reflected in the acquisition of Nettitude, a cyber security specialist in 2018.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Lloyd's Register has built a portfolio of digital, data and software solutions including greenfencetm, RTAMO and Seasafe.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Lloyd's Register's main office is located in London at 71 Fenchurch Street.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] It is one the many historic entities whose origin can be traced back to Lloyds Coffee House.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] It was towards the end of the nineteenth century before LR bought the Fenchurch Street site for £66,518.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Thomas Collcutt, one of the finest London architects of the time, was commissioned to design a new headquarters, with the emphasis on architectural splendour.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] LR took possession of the new building in December 1901.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] In the 1990s, Lloyd's Register knew it needed more office space in London and decided to build a new building in the courtyard behind the current building.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Richard Rogers was seen to now be as equally prestigious as Collcutt was, and was chosen to create a design for a new modern building on the site.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] The result is what is now known as the **Rogers Building**, with the original building renamed as the **Collcutt Building**.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Rogers created a two-tower glass, steel and concrete structure, opened by Queen Elizabeth II in November 2000, and which shouldn't be confused with the nearby Lloyd's building, the modern HQ of Lloyd's of London, also designed by Rogers.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Lloyd's Register also operates in more than 70 locations, serving clients based in 182 countries.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] In January 2024, Lloyd's Register signed a MOU with KEPCO, Zodiac Maritime and KSOE to assess rule requirements for the safe operation and regulatory compliance of nuclear powered bulk carriers and container ships to be designed and built by the consortium.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] LR's *Rules for Ships* are derived from principles of naval architecture and marine engineering, and govern safety and operational standards for numerous merchant, military, and privately owned vessels.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Specific editions of the rules are available to cater for merchant ships, naval ships, trimarans, special purpose vessels and offshore structures.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] A ship is known as being *in class* if she meets all the minimum requirements of LR's *Rules*, and such a status affects the possibility of a ship getting insurance.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Class can be withdrawn from a ship if she is in violation of any regulations and does not maintain the minimum requirements specified by the company.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] However, exceptional circumstances may warrant special dispensation from Lloyd's Register.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Any alteration to the vessel, whether it is a structural alteration or machinery, must be approved by Lloyd's Register before it is implemented.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Ships are inspected on a regular basis by a team of Lloyd's Register surveyors, one of the most important inspections being a ship's load line survey – due once every five years.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Such a survey includes an inspection of the hull to make sure that the load line has not been altered.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Numerous other inspections such as the condition of hatch and door seals, safety barriers, and guard rails are also performed.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Upon completion the ship is allowed to be operated for another year, and is issued a load line certificate.
[src:a/a1-at-lloyd-s] Lloyd's Register provide a list of rules and regulations to the public.
[src:a/ascii] ASCII encodes each code-point as a value from 0 to 127 – storable as a seven-bit integer.
[src:a/ascii] Ninety-five code-points are printable, including digits *0* to *9*, lowercase letters *a* to *z*, uppercase letters *A* to *Z*, and commonly used punctuation symbols.
[src:a/ascii] For example, the letter `i` is represented as 105 (decimal).
[src:a/ascii] Also, ASCII specifies 33 non-printing control codes which originated with Teletype devices, most of which are now obsolete.
[src:a/ascii] The control characters that are still commonly used include carriage return, line feed, and tab.
[src:a/ascii] ASCII lacks code-points for characters with diacritical marks and therefore does not directly support terms or names such as résumé, jalapeño, or René.
[src:a/ascii] But, depending on hardware and software support, some diacritical marks can be rendered by overwriting a letter with a backtick (`) or tilde (~).
[src:a/ascii] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) prefers the name **US-ASCII** for this character encoding.
[src:a/ascii] ASCII is the standardisation of a seven-bit teleprinter code developed in part from earlier telegraph codes.
[src:a/ascii] Work on the ASCII standard began in May 1961, when IBM engineer Bob Bemer submitted a proposal to the American Standards Association's (ASA) (now the American National Standards Institute or ANSI) X3.2 subcommittee.
[src:a/ascii] The first edition of the standard was published in 1963, contemporaneously with the introduction of the Teletype Model 33.
[src:a/ascii] It later underwent a major revision in 1967, and several further revisions until 1986.
[src:a/ascii] In contrast to earlier telegraph codes such as Baudot, ASCII was ordered for more convenient collation (especially alphabetical sorting of lists), and added controls for devices other than teleprinters.
[src:a/ascii] ASCII was developed under the auspices of a committee of the American Standards Association (ASA), called the X3 committee, by its X3.2 (later X3L2) subcommittee, and later by that subcommittee's X3.2.4 working group (now INCITS).
[src:a/ascii] The ASA later became the United States of America Standards Institute (USASI) and ultimately became the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:a/ascii] With the other special characters and control codes filled in, ASCII was published as ASA X3.4-1963, leaving 28 code positions without any assigned meaning, reserved for future standardization, and one unassigned control code.
[src:a/ascii] There was some debate at the time whether there should be more control characters rather than the lowercase alphabet.
[src:a/ascii] The indecision did not last long: during May 1963 the CCITT Working Party on the New Telegraph Alphabet proposed to assign lowercase characters to *sticks* 6 and 7, and International Organization for Standardization TC 97 SC 2 voted during October to incorporate the change into its draft standard.
[src:a/ascii] The X3.2.4 task group voted its approval for the change to ASCII at its May 1963 meeting.
[src:a/ascii] Locating the lowercase letters in *sticks* 6 and 7 caused the characters to differ in bit pattern from the upper case by a single bit, which simplified case-insensitive character matching and the construction of keyboards and printers.
[src:a/ascii] It added the brace and vertical bar characters.
[src:a/ascii] It renamed some control characters – SOM became SOH.
[src:a/ascii] It moved or removed others – RU was removed.
[src:a/ascii] The use of ASCII format for Network Interchange was described in 1969.
[src:a/ascii] That document was formally elevated to an Internet Standard in 2015.
[src:a/ascii] In the X3.15 standard, the X3 committee also addressed how ASCII should be transmitted (least significant bit first) and recorded on perforated tape.
[src:a/ascii] They proposed a 9-track standard for magnetic tape and attempted to deal with some punched card formats.
[src:a/ascii] The X3.2 subcommittee designed ASCII based on the earlier teleprinter encoding systems.
[src:a/ascii] Like other character encodings, ASCII specifies a correspondence between digital bit patterns and character symbols (i.e. graphemes and control characters).
[src:a/ascii] This allows digital devices to communicate with each other and to process, store, and communicate character-oriented information such as written language.
[src:a/ascii] Before ASCII was developed, the encodings in use included 26 alphabetic characters, 10 numerical digits, and from 11 to 25 special graphic symbols.
[src:a/ascii] To include all these, and control characters compatible with the Comité Consultatif International Téléphonique et Télégraphique (CCITT) International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:a/ascii] 2 (ITA2) standard of 1932, FIELDATA (1956), and early EBCDIC (1963), more than 64 codes were required for ASCII.
[src:a/ascii] ITA2 was in turn based on Baudot code, the 5-bit telegraph code Émile Baudot invented in 1870 and patented in 1874.
[src:a/ascii] The committee debated the possibility of a shift function (like in ITA2), which would allow more than 64 codes to be represented by a six-bit code.
[src:a/ascii] In a shifted code, some character codes determine choices between options for the following character codes.
[src:a/ascii] It allows compact encoding, but is less reliable for data transmission, as an error in transmitting the shift code typically makes a long part of the transmission unreadable.
[src:a/ascii] The standards committee decided against shifting, and so ASCII required at least a seven-bit code.
[src:a/ascii] The committee considered an eight-bit code, since eight bits (octets) would allow two four-bit patterns to efficiently encode two digits with binary-coded decimal.
[src:a/ascii] However, it would require all data transmission to send eight bits when seven could suffice.
[src:a/ascii] The committee voted to use a seven-bit code to minimize costs associated with data transmission.
[src:a/ascii] Since perforated tape at the time could record eight bits in one position, it also allowed for a parity bit for error checking if desired.
[src:a/ascii] Eight-bit machines (with octets as the native data type) that did not use parity checking typically set the eighth bit to 0.
[src:a/ascii] The code itself was patterned so that most control codes were together and all graphic codes were together, for ease of identification.
[src:a/ascii] The first two so-called *ASCII sticks* (32 positions) were reserved for control characters.
[src:a/ascii] The "space" character had to come before graphics to make sorting easier, so it became position 20hex; for the same reason, many special signs commonly used as separators were placed before digits.
[src:a/ascii] The committee decided it was important to support uppercase 64-character alphabets, and chose to pattern ASCII so it could be reduced easily to a usable 64-character set of graphic codes, as was done in the DEC SIXBIT code (1963).
[src:a/ascii] Lowercase letters were therefore not interleaved with uppercase.
[src:a/ascii] To keep options available for lowercase letters and other graphics, the special and numeric codes were arranged before the letters, and the letter *A* was placed in position 41hex to match the draft of the corresponding British standard.
[src:a/ascii] The digits 0–9 are prefixed with 011, but the remaining 4 bits correspond to their respective values in binary, making conversion with binary-coded decimal straightforward (for example, 5 is encoded to 011*0101*, where 5 is *0101* in binary).
[src:a/ascii] Many of the non-alphanumeric characters were positioned to correspond to their shifted position on typewriters; an important subtlety is that these were based on *mechanical* typewriters, not *electric* typewriters.
[src:a/ascii] Mechanical typewriters followed the *de facto* standard set by the Remington No.
[src:a/ascii] 2 (1878), the first typewriter with a shift key, and the shifted values of `23456789-` were `"#$%_&'()` – early typewriters omitted *0* and *1*, using *O* (capital letter *o*) and *l* (lowercase letter *L*) instead, but `1!` and `0)` pairs became standard once 0 and 1 became common.
[src:a/ascii] Thus, in ASCII `!"#$%` were placed in the second stick, positions 1–5, corresponding to the digits 1–5 in the adjacent stick.
[src:a/ascii] The parentheses could not correspond to *9* and *0*, however, because the place corresponding to *0* was taken by the space character.
[src:a/ascii] This was accommodated by removing `_` (underscore) from *6* and shifting the remaining characters, which corresponded to many European typewriters that placed the parentheses with *8* and *9*.
[src:a/ascii] This discrepancy from typewriters led to bit-paired keyboards, notably the Teletype Model 33, which used the left-shifted layout corresponding to ASCII, differently from traditional mechanical typewriters.
[src:a/ascii] 2, and the `,< .>` pairs were used on some keyboards (others, including the No.
[src:a/ascii] 2, did not shift `,` (comma) or `.` (full stop) so they could be used in uppercase without unshifting).
[src:a/ascii] However, ASCII split the `;:` pair (dating to No.
[src:a/ascii] 2), and rearranged mathematical symbols (varied conventions, commonly `-* =+`) to `:* ;+ -=`.
[src:a/ascii] Some then-common typewriter characters were not included, notably `½ ¼ ¢`, while ^ ` ~ were included as diacritics for international use, and `< >` for mathematical use, together with the simple line characters `\ |` (in addition to common `/`).
[src:a/ascii] The *@* symbol was not used in continental Europe and the committee expected it would be replaced by an accented *À* in the French variation, so the *@* was placed in position 40hex, right before the letter A.
[src:a/ascii] The control codes felt essential for data transmission were the start of message (SOM), end of address (EOA), end of message (EOM), end of transmission (EOT), "who are you?" (WRU), "are you?" (RU), a reserved device control (DC0), synchronous idle (SYNC), and acknowledge (ACK).
[src:a/ascii] These were positioned to maximize the Hamming distance between their bit patterns.
[src:a/ascii] ASCII-code order is also called *ASCIIbetical* order.
[src:a/ascii] Collation of data is sometimes done in this order rather than "standard" alphabetical order (collating sequence).
[src:a/ascii] An intermediate order converts uppercase letters to lowercase before comparing ASCII values.
[src:a/ascii] ASCII reserves the first 32 code points (numbers 0–31 decimal) and the last one (number 127 decimal) for control characters.
[src:a/ascii] These are codes intended to control peripheral devices (such as printers), or to provide meta-information about data streams, such as those stored on magnetic tape.
[src:a/ascii] Despite their name, these code points do not represent printable characters (i.e. they are not characters at all, but signals).
[src:a/ascii] For debugging purposes, "placeholder" symbols (such as those given in ISO 2047 and its predecessors) are assigned to them.
[src:a/ascii] For example, character 0x0A represents the "line feed" function (which causes a printer to advance its paper), and character 8 represents "backspace".
[src:a/ascii] RFC 2822 refers to control characters that do not include carriage return, line feed or white space as non-whitespace control characters.
[src:a/ascii] Except for the control characters that prescribe elementary line-oriented formatting, ASCII does not define any mechanism for describing the structure or appearance of text within a document.
[src:a/ascii] Other schemes, such as markup languages, address page and document layout and formatting.
[src:a/ascii] The original ASCII standard used only short descriptive phrases for each control character.
[src:a/ascii] The ambiguity this caused was sometimes intentional, such as when a character would be used slightly differently on a terminal link or in a data stream.
[src:a/ascii] Probably the most influential single device affecting the interpretation of these characters was the Teletype Model 33 ASR, which was a printing terminal with an available paper tape reader/punch option.
[src:a/ascii] Paper tape was a very popular medium for long-term program storage until the 1980s, less costly and in some ways less fragile than magnetic tape.
[src:a/ascii] In particular, the Teletype Model 33 machine assignments for codes 17 (control-Q, DC1, also known as XON), 19 (control-S, DC3, also known as XOFF), and 127 (delete) became *de facto* standards.
[src:a/ascii] The Model 33 was also notable for taking the description of control-G (code 7, BEL, meaning audibly alert the operator) literally, as the unit contained an actual bell which it rang when it received a BEL character.
[src:a/ascii] When a Teletype 33 ASR equipped with the automatic paper tape reader received a control-S (XOFF, an abbreviation for transmit off), it caused the tape reader to stop; receiving control-Q (XON, transmit on) caused the tape reader to resume.
[src:a/ascii] This so-called flow control technique became adopted by several early computer operating systems as a "handshaking" signal warning a sender to stop transmission because of impending buffer overflow; it persists to this day in many systems as a manual output control technique.
[src:a/ascii] On some systems, control-S retains its meaning, but control-Q is replaced by a second control-S to resume output.
[src:a/ascii] The 33 ASR also could be configured to employ control-R (DC2) and control-T (DC4) to start and stop the tape punch; on some units equipped with this function, the corresponding control character lettering on the keycap above the letter was TAPE and TAPE respectively.
[src:a/ascii] The Teletype could not move its typehead backwards, so it did not have a key on its keyboard to send a BS (backspace).
[src:a/ascii] Instead, there was a key marked RUB OUT that sent code 127 (DEL).
[src:a/ascii] The purpose of this key was to erase mistakes in a manually-input paper tape: the operator had to push a button on the tape punch to back it up, then type the rubout, which punched all holes and replaced the mistake with a character that was intended to be ignored.
[src:a/ascii] Teletypes were commonly used with the less-expensive computers from Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC); these systems had to use what keys were available, and thus the DEL character was assigned to erase the previous character.
[src:a/ascii] Because of this, DEC video terminals (by default) sent the DEL character for the key marked "Backspace" while the separate key marked "Delete" sent an escape sequence; many other competing terminals sent a BS character for the backspace key.
[src:a/ascii] The assumption that no key sent a BS character allowed Ctrl+H to be used for other purposes, such as the "help" prefix command in GNU Emacs.
[src:a/ascii] Many more of the control characters have been assigned meanings quite different from their original ones.
[src:a/ascii] The "escape" character (ESC, code 27), for example, was intended originally to allow sending of other control characters as literals instead of invoking their meaning, an "escape sequence".
[src:a/ascii] This is the same meaning of "escape" encountered in URL encodings, C language strings, and other systems where certain characters have a reserved meaning.
[src:a/ascii] Over time this interpretation has been co-opted and has eventually been changed.
[src:a/ascii] In modern usage, an ESC sent *to* the terminal usually indicates the start of a command sequence, which can be used to address the cursor, scroll a region, set/query various terminal properties, and more.
[src:a/ascii] They are usually in the form of a so-called "ANSI escape code" (often starting with a "Control Sequence Introducer", "CSI", "ESC [") from ECMA-48 (1972) and its successors.
[src:a/ascii] Some escape sequences do not have introducers, like the "Reset to Initial State", "RIS" command "ESC c".
[src:a/ascii] In contrast, an ESC read *from* the terminal is most often used as an out-of-band character used to terminate an operation or special mode, as in the TECO and vi text editors.
[src:a/ascii] In graphical user interface (GUI) and windowing systems, ESC generally causes an application to abort its current operation or to exit (terminate) altogether.
[src:a/ascii] The reapplication of some control characters to new meanings created problems when transferring "plain text" files between systems.
[src:a/ascii] The best example of this is the newline problem in various operating systems.
[src:a/ascii] Teletype machines required that a line of text be terminated with a "carriage return" (to move the printhead to the beginning of the line) followed by a "line feed" (to advance the paper by one line).
[src:a/ascii] The name "carriage return" comes from the fact that, on a manual typewriter, the carriage holding the paper moves while the typebars that strike the ribbon remain stationary.
[src:a/ascii] The entire carriage must be pushed to the right ("returned") in order to position the paper for the next line.
[src:a/ascii] DEC operating systems (OS/8, RT-11, RSX-11, RSTS, TOPS-10, etc.) stored both characters at the end of each line in textual files, as needed by Teletype machines.
[src:a/ascii] When so-called "glass TTYs" were introduced (later called CRTs or "dumb terminals"), they followed the same logic, expecting the same CR and LF characters.
[src:a/ascii] When Gary Kildall created CP/M, he was inspired by some of the command line interface conventions used in DEC's RT-11 operating system.
[src:a/ascii] Until the introduction of IBM PC DOS in 1981, IBM had no influence in this, because their 1970s operating systems used EBCDIC encoding instead of ASCII and they were oriented toward punch-card input and line printer output on which the concept of "carriage return" was meaningless.
[src:a/ascii] IBM's PC DOS (also marketed as MS-DOS by Microsoft) inherited the CRLF convention by virtue of being loosely based on CP/M, and Windows, in turn, inherited it from MS-DOS.
[src:a/ascii] Placing CR and LF at the end of each line in a plain text document or data stream reflects what terminals and printers needed to receive, to display that material.
[src:a/ascii] Multics introduced an innovation: it used only one character (LF), to represent the end of the line in stored files and in data streams.
[src:a/ascii] Upon output, the tty driver converts the LF to CRLF, so files can be printed to a terminal without needing a command to explicitly convert the file format.
[src:a/ascii] Unix and Unix-like systems adopted this design from Multics, as did Amiga systems.
[src:a/ascii] UNIX documents say "newline" or "NL" to refer to the line terminator.
[src:a/ascii] Contrarily, the Radio Shack TRS-80, Apple DOS, Apple ProDOS, and classic Mac OS used a lone carriage return (CR) to terminate lines.
[src:a/ascii] Apple's later operating system, Mac OS X (now called macOS) is based on Unix, so it uses line feed (LF).
[src:a/ascii] To enable communication between all these systems, the Telnet protocol defined a "Network Virtual Terminal" (NVT), wherein a single text format (ASCII with CR-LF line endings) was used for transmission and each system converted to/from its own native representation.
[src:a/ascii] The File Transfer Protocol adopted the Telnet protocol, including the Network Virtual Terminal, for transmitting commands and for transferring textual files (known as "ASCII mode").
[src:a/ascii] The World Wide Web's HTTP uses a modified NVT: the standard allows lone CR and LF characters but requires that each be interpreted as an NVT CRLF.
[src:a/ascii] Complexity arose in network-facing systems that didn't follow the NVT mechanism, such as some version control systems.
[src:a/ascii] Bugs sometimes expose a system's native implementation to other systems on the Internet, causing data corruption.
[src:a/ascii] The PDP-6 monitor, and its PDP-10 successor TOPS-10, used control-Z (SUB) as an end-of-file indication for input from a terminal.
[src:a/ascii] Some operating systems such as CP/M tracked file length only in units of disk blocks, and used control-Z to mark the end of the actual text in the file.
[src:a/ascii] For these reasons, EOF, or end-of-file, was used colloquially and conventionally as a three-letter acronym for control-Z instead of SUBstitute.
[src:a/ascii] The end-of-text character (ETX), also known as control-C, was inappropriate for a variety of reasons, while using control-Z as the control character to end a file is analogous to the letter Z's position at the end of the alphabet, and serves as a very convenient mnemonic aid.
[src:a/ascii] A historically common and still prevalent convention uses the ETX character convention to interrupt and halt a program via an input data stream, usually from a keyboard.
[src:a/ascii] The Unix terminal driver uses the end-of-transmission character (EOT), also known as control-D, to indicate the end of a data stream.
[src:a/ascii] In the C programming language, and in Unix conventions, the null character is used to terminate text strings; such null-terminated strings can be known in abbreviation as ASCIZ or ASCIIZ, where here Z stands for "zero".
[src:a/ascii] Other representations might be used by specialist equipment, for example ISO 2047 graphics or hexadecimal numbers.
[src:a/ascii] At the time of adoption, the codes 20hex to 7Ehex would cause the printing of a visible character (a glyph), and thus were designated "printable characters".
[src:a/ascii] These codes represent letters, digits, punctuation marks, and a few miscellaneous symbols.
[src:a/ascii] There are 95 printable characters in total.
[src:a/ascii] The empty space between words, as produced by the space bar of a keyboard, is character code 20hex.
[src:a/ascii] Since the space character is visible in printed text it considered a "printable character", even though it is unique in having no visible glyph.
[src:a/ascii] It is listed in the printable character table, as per the ASCII standard, instead of in the control character table.
[src:a/ascii] Code 7Fhex corresponds to the non-printable "delete" (DEL) control character and is listed in the control character table.
[src:a/ascii] Earlier versions of ASCII used the up arrow instead of the caret (5Ehex) and the left arrow instead of the underscore (5Fhex).
[src:a/ascii] ASCII was first used commercially during 1963 as a seven-bit teleprinter code for American Telephone & Telegraph's TWX (TeletypeWriter eXchange) network.
[src:a/ascii] TWX originally used the earlier five-bit ITA2, which was also used by the competing Telex teleprinter system.
[src:a/ascii] Bob Bemer introduced features such as the escape sequence.
[src:a/ascii] His British colleague Hugh McGregor Ross helped to popularize this work – according to Bemer, "so much so that the code that was to become ASCII was first called the *Bemer–Ross Code* in Europe".
[src:a/ascii] Because of his extensive work on ASCII, Bemer has been called "the father of ASCII".
[src:a/ascii] On March 11, 1968, US President Lyndon B.
[src:a/ascii] ASCII was the most common character encoding on the World Wide Web until December 2007, when the UTF-8 encoding surpassed it; UTF-8 is backward compatible with ASCII.
[src:a/ascii] As computer technology spread throughout the world, different standards bodies and corporations developed many variations of ASCII to facilitate the expression of non-English languages that used Roman-based alphabets.
[src:a/ascii] One could class some of these variations as "ASCII extensions", although some misuse that term to represent all variants, including those that do not preserve ASCII's character-map in the 7-bit range.
[src:a/ascii] Furthermore, the ASCII extensions have also been mislabelled as ASCII.
[src:a/ascii] From early in its development, ASCII was intended to be just one of several national variants of an international character code standard.
[src:a/ascii] Almost every country needed an adapted version of ASCII, since ASCII suited the needs of only the US and a few other countries.
[src:a/ascii] For example, Canada had its own version that supported French characters.
[src:a/ascii] Many other countries developed variants of ASCII to include non-English letters (e.g. é, ñ, ß, Ł), currency symbols (e.g. £, ¥), etc.
[src:a/ascii] It would share most characters in common, but assign other locally useful characters to several code points reserved for "national use".
[src:a/ascii] ISO/IEC 646, like ASCII, is a 7-bit character set.
[src:a/ascii] It does not make any additional codes available, so the same code points encoded different characters in different countries.
[src:a/ascii] C trigraphs were created to solve this problem for ANSI C, although their late introduction and inconsistent implementation in compilers limited their use.
[src:a/ascii] Many programmers kept their computers on ASCII, so plain-text in Swedish, German etc.
[src:a/ascii] (for example, in e-mail or Usenet) contained "{, }" and similar variants in the middle of words, something those programmers got used to.
[src:a/ascii] For example, a Swedish programmer mailing another programmer asking if they should go for lunch, could get "N{ jag har sm|rg}sar" as the answer, which should be "Nä jag har smörgåsar" meaning "No I've got sandwiches".
[src:a/ascii] In Japan and Korea, still as of the 2020s, a variation of ASCII is used, in which the backslash (5C hex) is rendered as ¥ (a Yen sign, in Japan) or ₩ (a Won sign, in Korea).
[src:a/ascii] This means that, for example, the file path C:\Users\Smith is shown as C:¥Users¥Smith (in Japan) or C:₩Users₩Smith (in Korea).
[src:a/ascii] In Europe, teletext character sets, which are variants of ASCII, are used for broadcast TV subtitles, defined by World System Teletext and broadcast using the DVB-TXT standard for embedding teletext into DVB transmissions.
[src:a/ascii] In the case that the subtitles were initially authored for teletext and converted, the derived subtitle formats are constrained to the same character sets.
[src:a/ascii] Eventually, as 8-, 16-, and 32-bit (and later 64-bit) computers began to replace 12-, 18-, and 36-bit computers as the norm, it became common to use an 8-bit byte to store each character in memory, providing an opportunity for extended, 8-bit relatives of ASCII.
[src:a/ascii] In most cases these developed as true extensions of ASCII, leaving the original character-mapping intact, but adding additional character definitions after the first 128 (i.e., 7-bit) characters.
[src:a/ascii] ASCII itself remained a seven-bit code: the term "extended ASCII" has no official status.
[src:a/ascii] For some countries, 8-bit extensions of ASCII were developed that included support for characters used in local languages (for example, ISCII for India and VISCII for Vietnam).
[src:a/ascii] Even for markets where it was not necessary to add many characters to support additional languages, manufacturers of early home computer systems often developed their own 8-bit extensions of ASCII to include additional characters, such as box-drawing characters, semigraphics, and video game sprites.
[src:a/ascii] Often, these additions also replaced control characters (index 0 to 31, as well as index 127) with even more platform-specific extensions.
[src:a/ascii] In other cases, the extra bit was used for some other purpose, such as toggling inverse video; this approach was used by ATASCII, an extension of ASCII developed by Atari.
[src:a/ascii] Most ASCII extensions are based on ASCII-1967 (the current standard), but some extensions are instead based on the earlier ASCII-1963.
[src:a/ascii] For example, PETSCII, which was developed by Commodore International for their 8-bit systems, is based on ASCII-1963.
[src:a/ascii] Likewise, many Sharp MZ character sets are based on ASCII-1963.
[src:a/ascii] IBM defined code page 437 for the IBM PC, replacing the control characters with graphic symbols such as smiley faces, and mapping additional graphic characters to the upper 128 positions.
[src:a/ascii] Digital Equipment Corporation developed the Multinational Character Set (DEC-MCS) for use in the popular VT220 terminal as one of the first extensions designed more for international languages than for block graphics.
[src:a/ascii] Apple defined Mac OS Roman for the Macintosh and Adobe defined the PostScript Standard Encoding for PostScript; both sets contained "international" letters, typographic symbols and punctuation marks instead of graphics, more like modern character sets.
[src:a/ascii] The ISO/IEC 8859 standard (derived from the DEC-MCS) provided a standard that most systems copied (or at least were based on, when not copied exactly).
[src:a/ascii] A popular further extension designed by Microsoft, Windows-1252 (often mislabeled as ISO-8859-1), added the typographic punctuation marks needed for traditional text printing.
[src:a/ascii] ISO-8859-1, Windows-1252, and the original 7-bit ASCII were the most common character encoding methods on the World Wide Web until 2008, when UTF-8 overtook them.
[src:a/ascii] ISO/IEC 4873 introduced 32 additional control codes defined in the 80–9F hexadecimal range, as part of extending the 7-bit ASCII encoding to become an 8-bit system.
[src:a/ascii] Unicode and the ISO/IEC 10646 Universal Character Set (UCS) have a much wider array of characters and their various encoding forms have begun to supplant ISO/IEC 8859 and ASCII rapidly in many environments.
[src:a/ascii] While ASCII is limited to 128 characters, Unicode and the UCS support more characters by separating the concepts of unique identification (using natural numbers called *code points*) and encoding (to 8-, 16-, or 32-bit binary formats, called UTF-8, UTF-16, and UTF-32, respectively).
[src:a/ascii] ASCII was incorporated into the Unicode (1991) character set as the first 128 symbols, so the 7-bit ASCII characters have the same numeric codes in both sets.
[src:a/ascii] This allows UTF-8 to be backward compatible with 7-bit ASCII, as a UTF-8 file containing only ASCII characters is identical to an ASCII file containing the same sequence of characters.
[src:a/ascii] Even more importantly, forward compatibility is ensured as software that recognizes only 7-bit ASCII characters as special and does not alter bytes with the highest bit set (as is often done to support 8-bit ASCII extensions such as ISO-8859-1) will preserve UTF-8 data unchanged.
[src:a/azerty] The competing layouts devised for French (e.g. the 1907 ZHJAY layout, Arav Dixit's 1976 layout, the 2002 Dvorak-fr, and the 2005 BÉPO layout) have obtained only limited recognition, although the latter has been included in the 2019 French keyboard layout standard.
[src:a/azerty] The AZERTY layout appeared in France in the last decade of the 19th century as a variation on American QWERTY typewriters.
[src:a/azerty] It was more successful than its contemporaries (e.g. the French ZHJAYS layout created by Albert Navarre in the early 20th century) because of its similarity to the QWERTY layout and its initial popularity.
[src:a/azerty] In France, the AZERTY layout is the de facto norm for keyboards.
[src:a/azerty] In 1976, a QWERTY layout adapted to the French language was put forward, as an experimental standard (NF XP E55-060) by AFNOR.
[src:a/azerty] This standard made provision for a temporary adaptation period during which the letters A, Q, Z and W could be positioned as in the traditional AZERTY layout.
[src:a/azerty] In January 2016, the French Culture Ministry looked to replace the industrial AZERTY layout with one more suited to French.
[src:a/azerty] A standard was published by the French national organization for standardization in 2019.
[src:a/azerty] The AZERTY layout is used in France, Belgium and some African countries.
[src:a/azerty] The French and Belgian AZERTY keyboards also have special characters used in the French and Dutch language, such as é, è, ê, ï, ë, ... and other characters such as &, ", ', and ç (only for French), some located under the numbers and some with combinations of keys.
[src:a/azerty] Certain letters are accented frequently enough that they are given their own keys rather than being used in combination with a dead key.
[src:a/azerty] A dead key serves to modify the appearance of the next character to be typed on the keyboard.
[src:a/azerty] Dead keys are mainly used to generate accents (or diacritics) on vowels.
[src:a/azerty] A circumflex can be generated by first striking the ^ key (located to the right of P in most AZERTY layouts), then the vowel requiring the accent (with the exception of y).
[src:a/azerty] For example, pressing ^ then a produces **â**.
[src:a/azerty] A diaresis can be generated by striking the ¨ key (in most AZERTY layouts, it is generated by combining the ⇧+^ keys), then the vowel requiring the accent.
[src:a/azerty] For example, pressing ⇧+^ then a produces **ä**.
[src:a/azerty] The grave accent can be generated by striking the ` key (in the French AZERTY layout it is located to the right of the ù key) on Macintosh keyboards, while on PC-type keyboards it can be generated by using the combination Alt Gr+è.
[src:a/azerty] In the Belgian AZERTY layout, the grave accent is generated by the combination Alt Gr+μ (the μ key is located to the right of the ù key on Belgian AZERTY keyboards), and then the key for the vowel requiring the accent.
[src:a/azerty] Its main use is in typing letters used in other languages (e.g.
[src:a/azerty] Italian **ò**) and accented capital letters.
[src:a/azerty] The acute accent is available under Windows by the use of Alt+a, then the vowel requiring the accent.
[src:a/azerty] The **é** combination can be generated using its own key.
[src:a/azerty] For Linux users, it can be generated using ⇪ Caps Lock+é then the vowel.
[src:a/azerty] On a Macintosh AZERTY keyboard, the acute accent is generated by a combination of the Alt+⇧+&, keys, followed by the vowel.
[src:a/azerty] In the Belgian AZERTY layout, a vowel with an acute accent can be generated by a combination of Alt Gr+ù, then the vowel.
[src:a/azerty] The acute accent is not available in the French layout on Windows.
[src:a/azerty] The tilde is available under Windows by using a combination of the Alt Gr+é keys, followed by the letter requiring the tilde.
[src:a/azerty] On Macs, the **ñ** can be obtained by the combination of Alt Gr+N keys, followed by the N key.
[src:a/azerty] In the Belgian AZERTY layout, **ñ** can be generated by a combination of Alt Gr+=.
[src:a/azerty] Spanish **ñ**, Portuguese **ã** and **õ**) and accented capital letters.
[src:a/azerty] With some operating systems, the Alt key generates characters by means of their individual codes.
[src:a/azerty] In order to obtain characters, the Alt key must be pressed and held down while typing the relevant code into the numeric keypad.
[src:a/azerty] On Linux, the Alt key gives direct access to French-language special characters.
[src:a/azerty] The ligatures **œ** and **æ** can be keyed in by using Alt Gr+o and Alt Gr+a respectively, in the fr-oss keyboard layout; their uppercase equivalents can be generated using the same key combinations plus the ⇧ Shift key.
[src:a/azerty] Other useful punctuation symbols, such as **≤**, **≥**, or **≠**, can be more easily accessed in the same way.
[src:a/azerty] In X11, the window system common to many flavors of UNIX, the keyboard interface is completely configurable, allowing each user to assign different functions to each key in line with their personal preferences.
[src:a/azerty] For example, specific combinations of Alt Gr key could be assigned to many other characters.
[src:a/azerty] It is possible to fill in these gaps by installing a keyboard driver that has been specially enriched for the French language.
[src:a/azerty] One can also use WinCompose in order to easily type all characters.
[src:a/azerty] The character `Ç` could be typed by pressing ⎄ Compose , C or the character `«` with ⎄ Compose < <, and there is also an option to allow typing accentuated capitals with ⇪ Caps Lock such that `Ç` can be typed with ⇪ Caps Lock ç.
[src:a/azerty] Some word-processing software packages address some of these gaps.
[src:a/azerty] The non-breaking space can be obtained by pressing Ctrl followed by a space, in a word-processing package such as OpenOffice.org Writer, or by using Ctrl+⇧+Espace [Spacebar] in Microsoft Word.
[src:a/azerty] In January 2016, the French Ministry of Culture, which is in charge of language affairs, expressed a will to offer an alternative to the AZERTY layouts traditionally proposed by the industry.
[src:a/azerty] The new layout would have to provide full coverage of the symbols required by French spelling (including accented capitals such as É) as well as other languages of France and European languages written with the Latin alphabet.
[src:a/azerty] The project, led by the French national organization for standardization AFNOR, released both this improved AZERTY and a BÉPO layout.
[src:a/azerty] Initially due in January 2018, the standard was released in April 2019.
[src:a/azerty] The layout keeps the same placement for the 26 Latin letters and 10 digits, but moves others (such as some accented letters and punctuation signs), while it adds a range of other symbols (accessible with Shift, AltGr).
[src:a/azerty] There is easy access to guillemets « » (French quotes), accented capital letters: À, É, Ç, as well as Œ/œ, Æ/æ, which was not possible before on basic AZERTY (Windows' AZERTY); previously alt codes were required.
[src:a/azerty] It allows typing words in many languages using dead keys, which are in blue on the picture, to access a variety of diacritics.
[src:a/azerty] A few mathematics symbols have also been added.
[src:a/azerty] A website for the new AZERTY layout has been created, offering information, visuals of the changes, links to drivers to install the layout and various other resources.
[src:a/azerty] The Belgian AZERTY keyboard allows for the placing of accents on vowels without recourse to encoding via the Alt key + code.
[src:a/azerty] This is made possible by the provision of dead keys for each type of accent: ◌̂ ◌̈ ◌́ ◌̀ (the last two being generated by the combinations Alt Gr+ù and Alt Gr+μ respectively).
[src:a/azerty] The description *partially dead* means that pressing the key in question sometimes generates the desired symbol directly, but that at least one of the symbols represented on the key will only appear after a second key has been pressed.
[src:a/azerty] In order to obtain a symbol in isolation, the space bar must be pressed, otherwise a vowel should be pressed to generate the desired accented form.
[src:a/azerty] The other keys are identical, even though traditionally the names of special keys are printed on them in English.
[src:a/azerty] This is because Belgium is predominantly bilingual (French-Dutch) and officially trilingual (a third language, German, is spoken in the East Cantons).
[src:a/azerty] The key to the right of 0 on the numeric keypad corresponds either to the full stop or to the comma (which is why there are two distinct keyboard drivers under Windows).
[src:a/azerty] The AZERTY keyboard as used in Flanders, the Dutch-speaking part of Belgium, uses the name *shift* instead of *maj* and *caps lock* instead of *verr maj*.
[src:a/azerty] Owing to its widespread usage in France, Belgium and some African countries, the AZERTY layout has several variants.
[src:a/azerty] French-speaking people in Canada use the Canadian Multilingual standard keyboard.
[src:a/azerty] It is the only keyboard layout provided by Microsoft Windows that allows to type the grapheme "Œ/œ", needed by French spelling.
[src:a/azerty] The "US-International" QWERTY layout supports French to the same extent than the Portugal's layout does (diacritics as dead keys, French guillemets, but no "œ/Œ").
[src:a/azerty] Some programmers prefer it over AZERTY, as it is closer to an international standard and allows easier input of ASCII punctuation characters which are used pervasively in programming languages.
[src:a/azerty] It can be used on a plain US-QWERTY keyboard, being an extension of it.
[src:a/azerty] However, only AZERTY is widely sold in French shops.
[src:a/azerty] Another alternative is the BÉPO layout, a French-language application of Dvorak's principles for ergonomic typing.
[src:a/azerty] As of 2024, only a few specialized manufacturers sell keyboards with the BÉPO layout printed on it; however, its practitioners use to type blindly, without looking at the keys, for increased efficiency, if at a higher learning cost.
[src:a/azerty] Apple's keyboards use the same AZERTY layout in both France and Belgium.
[src:a/azerty] Based on the Belgian version, the most notable differences are the locations for the @-sign and €-sign, among others.
[src:a/azerty] MacOS also supports the standard French layout for non-Apple keyboards; the standard Belgian layout, however, is available through third-party support only.
[src:a/azerty] There is an Arabic variant of the AZERTY keyboard.
[src:a/azerty] It is especially used in the African countries Algeria, Chad, Comoros, Djibouti, Mauritania, Morocco, Tunisia and in Arab communities in French-speaking countries to be able to type both in Arabic and in French.
[src:a/azerty] The *Tamazight (Latin)* standards-compliant layout is optimised for a wide range of Tamazight (Berber) language variants – including Tuareg variants – rather than French, though French can still be typed quickly.
[src:a/azerty] It installs as "Tamazight_L" and can be used both on the French locale and with Tamazight locales.
[src:a/azerty] QWERTY and QWERTZ adaptations of the layout are available for the physical keyboards used by major Amazigh (Berber) communities around the world.
[src:a/azerty] Other layouts exist for closer backwards compatibility with the French layout.
[src:a/azerty] All the above layouts were designed by the Universal Amazigh Keyboard Project and are available from there.
[src:a/azerty] There is also a Vietnamese variant of the AZERTY keyboard.
[src:a/azerty] It was especially used in Vietnamese typewriters made until the 1980s.
[src:a/azerty] Wolof keyboards also use AZERTY and are supported by Microsoft Windows (Windows 7 and later only).
[src:a/page] The **at sign** (**@**) is a typographical symbol used as an accounting and invoice abbreviation meaning "at a rate of" (e.g.
[src:a/page] 7 widgets @ £2 per widget = £14), and now seen more widely in email addresses and social media platform handles.
[src:a/page] In English, it is normally read aloud as "at", and is also commonly called the **at symbol**, **commercial at (commat)**, or **email address sign**.
[src:a/page] Most languages have their own name for the symbol.
[src:a/page] Although not included on the keyboard layout of the earliest commercially successful typewriters, it was on at least one 1889 model and the very successful Underwood models from the "Underwood No.
[src:a/page] It started to be used in email addresses in the 1970s, and is now routinely included on most types of computer keyboards.
[src:a/page] The earliest yet discovered symbol in this shape is found in a 1345 Bulgarian translation of a Greek chronicle written by Constantinos Manasses.
[src:a/page] Held today in the Vatican Apostolic Library, the initial letter of the word амин [amen] looks like an at sign.
[src:a/page] The symbol has long been used in Catalan, Spanish and Portuguese as an abbreviation of *arroba*, a unit of weight equivalent to 25 pounds, and derived from the Arabic expression of "the quarter" (الربع pronounced *ar-rubʿ*).
[src:a/page] A symbol resembling an @ is found in the Spanish *"Taula de Ariza"*, a registry to denote a wheat shipment from Castile to Aragon, in 1448.
[src:a/page] The document is about commerce with Pizarro, in particular the price of an @ of wine in Peru.
[src:a/page] The symbol could also mean *adi* (standard Italian *addì*, i. e.
[src:a/page] 'on the day of') as used on a health pass in Northern Italy in 1667.
[src:a/page] In 2010, the Museum of Modern Art (MoMA) added the @ symbol to its design collection.
[src:a/page] In 2025, it was also included in MoMA's *Pirouette: Turning Points in Design*, an exhibition of "widely recognized design icons [...] highlighting pivotal moments in design history," alongside the I ♥ NY logo, Google map pins, and original 1980s Mac GUI icons, and the NASA *Worm* insignia.
[src:a/page] The name of the symbol arises from its original use in showing quantities and their price per unit – for example, "10 widgets @ £1.50 each".
[src:a/page] The precise origin of the symbol is uncertain.
[src:a/page] The absence of a single English word for the symbol has prompted some writers to use the French *arobase*, to coin new words such as ***ampersat*** and ***asperand***, or to use the (visual) onomatopoeia *strudel*, but none of these have achieved wide use.
[src:a/page] In contemporary English usage, @ is a commercial symbol, meaning *at* and *at the rate of* or *at the price of*.
[src:a/page] It has rarely been used in financial ledgers, and is not used in standard typography.
[src:a/page] In 2012, "@" was registered as a trademark with the German Patent and Trade Mark Office.
[src:a/page] A cancellation request was filed in 2013, and the cancellation was ultimately confirmed by the German Federal Patent Court in 2017.
[src:a/page] A common contemporary use of @ is in email addresses (using the SMTP system), as in `jdoe@example.com` (the user `jdoe` located *at* the domain `example.com`).
[src:a/page] Ray Tomlinson of BBN Technologies is credited for having introduced this usage in 1971.
[src:a/page] On web pages, organizations often obscure the email addresses of their members or employees by omitting the @.
[src:a/page] This practice, known as address munging, attempts to make the email addresses less vulnerable to spam programs that scan the internet for them.
[src:a/page] On many social media platforms and forums, usernames or handles prefixed with an @ (in the form `@johndoe`) are interpreted as mentions of that user and may be treated specially.
[src:a/page] On online forums without threaded discussions, @ is commonly used to denote a reply; for instance: `@Jane` to respond to a comment Jane made earlier.
[src:a/page] Similarly, in some cases, @ is used for "attention" in email messages originally sent to someone else.
[src:a/page] For example, if an email was sent from Catherine to Steve, but in the body of the email, Catherine wants to make Keirsten aware of something, Catherine will start the line `@Keirsten` to signal to Keirsten that the following sentence concerns her.
[src:a/page] This also helps with mobile email users who might not see bold or color in email.
[src:a/page] In microblogging (such as on Twitter, GNU social- and ActivityPub-based microblogs), an @ before the user name is used to send publicly readable replies (e.g.
[src:a/page] The blog and client system interpret these as links to the user in question.
[src:a/page] When included as part of a person's or company's contact details, an @ symbol followed by a name is normally understood to refer to a Twitter handle.
[src:a/page] A similar use of the @ symbol was added to Facebook on September 15, 2009.
[src:a/page] In Internet Relay Chat (IRC), it is shown before users' nicknames to denote they have operator status on a channel.
[src:a/page] @ is used in various programming languages and other computer languages, although there is not a consistent theme to its usage.
[src:a/page] In Spanish, where many words end in "-o" when in the masculine gender and end "-a" in the feminine, @ is sometimes used as a gender-neutral substitute for the default "o" ending.
[src:a/page] For example, the word *amigos* traditionally represents not only male friends, but also a mixed group, or where the genders are not known.
[src:a/page] The proponents of gender-inclusive language would replace it with *amig@s* in these latter two cases, and use *amigos* only when the group referred to is all-male and *amigas* only when the group is all female.
[src:a/page] The Real Academia Española disapproves of this usage.
[src:a/page] In many languages other than English, although most typewriters included the symbol, the use of @ was less common before email became widespread in the mid-1990s.
[src:a/page] Consequently, it is often perceived in those languages as denoting "the Internet", computerization, or modernization in general.
[src:a/page] Naming the symbol after animals is also common.
